# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cidr-subnetting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] IP addresses are described as consisting of two groups of bits in the address: the most significant bits are the network prefix, which identifies a whole network or subnet, and the least significant set forms the *host identifier*, which specifies a particular interface of a host on that network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] This division is used as the basis of traffic routing between IP networks and for address allocation policies.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Whereas classful network design for IPv4 sized the network prefix as one or more eight-bit groups, resulting in the blocks of Class A, B, or C addresses, under CIDR address space, is allocated to Internet service providers (ISPs) and end users on any address-bit boundary.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In IPv6, however, the interface identifier has a fixed size of 64 bits by convention, and smaller subnets are never allocated to end users.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is based on **variable-length subnet masking** (**VLSM**), in which network prefixes have variable length as opposed to the fixed-length prefixing of the previous classful network design.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The main benefit of this is that it grants finer control of the sizes of subnets allocated to organizations, hence slowing the exhaustion of IPv4 addresses from the allocation of larger subnets than needed.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR gave rise to a new way of writing IP addresses known as CIDR notation, in which an IP address is followed by a suffix indicating the number of bits of the prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Blocks of addresses having contiguous prefixes may be aggregated as supernets, reducing the number of entries in the global routing table.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Each IP address consists of a network prefix followed by a host identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In the classful network architecture of IPv4, the three most significant bits of the 32-bit IP address defined the size of the network prefix for unicast networking, and determined the network class A, B, or C.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The advantage of this system is that the network prefix can be determined for any IP address without any further information.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The disadvantage is that networks were usually too big or too small for most organizations to use, because only three sizes were available.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The smallest allocation and routing block contained 28 = 256 addresses, larger than necessary for personal or department networks, but too small for most enterprises.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The next larger block contained 216 = 65536 addresses, too large to be used efficiently even by large organizations.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] But for network users who needed more than 65536 addresses, the only other size (224) provided far too many, more than 16 million.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] This led to inefficiencies in address use as well as inefficiencies in routing, because it required a large number of allocated class-C networks with individual route announcements, being geographically dispersed with little opportunity for route aggregation.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Within a decade after the invention of the Domain Name System (DNS), the classful network method was found not scalable.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] This led to the development of subnetting and CIDR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The formerly meaningful class distinctions based on the most-significant address bits were abandoned and the new system was described as "classless", in contrast to the old system, which became known as "classful".
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Routing protocols were revised to carry not just IP addresses, but also their subnet masks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Implementing CIDR required every host and router on the Internet to be reprogrammed in small ways—no small feat at a time when the Internet was entering a period of rapid growth.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In 1993, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a new set of standards, RFC 1518 and RFC 1519, to define this new principle for allocating IP address blocks and routing IPv4 packets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] An updated version, RFC 4632, was published in 2006.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] After a period of experimentation with various alternatives, Classless Inter-Domain Routing was based on variable-length subnet masking (VLSM), which allows each network to be divided into subnetworks of various power-of-two sizes, so that each subnetwork can be sized appropriately for local needs.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Variable-length subnet masks were mentioned as one alternative in RFC 950.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Techniques for grouping addresses for common operations were based on the concept of cluster addressing, first proposed by Carl-Herbert Rokitansky.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The address may denote a specific interface address (including a host identifier, such as *10.0.0.1/8*), or it may be the beginning address of an entire network (using a host identifier of 0, as in *10.0.0.0/8* or its equivalent *10/8*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR notation can even be used with no IP address at all, e.g. when referring to a */24* as a generic description of an IPv4 network that has a 24-bit prefix and 8-bit host numbers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In IPv4, CIDR notation came into wide use only after the implementation of the method, which was documented using dotted-decimal subnet mask specification after the slash, for example, *192.24.12.0/255.255.252.0*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Describing the network prefix width as a single number (*192.24.12.0/22*) was easier for network administrators to conceptualize and to calculate.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] It became gradually incorporated into later standards documents and into network configuration interfaces.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The number of addresses of a network may be calculated as 2address length − prefix length, where "address length" is 128 for IPv6 and 32 for IPv4.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, in IPv4, the prefix length */29* gives: 232−29 = 23 = 8 addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] A subnet mask is a bitmask that encodes the prefix length associated with an IPv4 address or network in quad-dotted notation: 32 bits, starting with a number of ones equal to the prefix length, ending with zeros, and encoded in four-part dotted-decimal format: *255.255.255.0*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] A subnet mask encodes the same information as a prefix length but predates the advent of CIDR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In CIDR notation, the prefix bits are always contiguous.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Subnet masks were allowed by RFC 950 to specify non-contiguous bits until RFC 4632 stated that the mask must consist of only contiguous ones, if any, in the more significant bits and contiguous zeroes, if any, in the less significant bits.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Given this constraint, a subnet mask and CIDR notation serve exactly the same function.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is principally a bitwise, prefix-based standard for the representation of IP addresses and their routing properties.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] It facilitates routing by allowing blocks of addresses to be grouped into single routing table entries.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] These groups, commonly called CIDR blocks, share an initial sequence of bits in the binary representation of their IP addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] IPv4 CIDR blocks are identified using a syntax similar to that of IPv4 addresses: a dotted-decimal address, followed by a slash, then a number from 0 to 32, i.e., *a.b.c.d/n*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The dotted-decimal portion is the IPv4 address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The number following the slash is the prefix length, the number of shared initial bits, counting from the most-significant bit of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] When emphasizing only the size of a network, the address portion of the notation is usually omitted.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Thus, a /20 block is a CIDR block with an unspecified 20-bit prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] An IP address is part of a CIDR block and is said to match the CIDR prefix if the initial n bits of the address and the CIDR prefix are the same.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] An IPv4 address is 32 bits so an n-bit CIDR prefix leaves 32−n bits unmatched, meaning that 232−n IPv4 addresses match a given n-bit CIDR prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Shorter CIDR prefixes match more addresses, while longer prefixes match fewer.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In the case of overlaid CIDR blocks, an address can match multiple CIDR prefixes of different lengths.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is also used for IPv6 addresses and the syntax semantic is identical.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The prefix length can range from 0 to 128, due to the larger number of bits in the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] However, by convention, a subnet on broadcast MAC layer networks always has 64-bit host identifiers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Larger prefixes (/127) are only used on some point-to-point links between routers, for security and policy reasons.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) issues to regional Internet registries (RIRs) large, short-prefix CIDR blocks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] However, a */8* (with over sixteen million addresses) is the largest block IANA will allocate.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, *62.0.0.0/8* is administered by RIPE NCC, the European RIR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The RIRs, each responsible for a single, large geographic area, such as Europe or North America, subdivide these blocks and allocate subnets to local Internet registries (LIRs).
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Similar subdividing may be repeated several times at lower levels of delegation.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] End-user networks receive subnets sized according to their projected short-term need.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Networks served by a single ISP are encouraged by IETF recommendations to obtain IP address space directly from their ISP.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Networks served by multiple ISPs, on the other hand, may obtain provider-independent address space directly from the appropriate RIR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, in the late 1990s, the IP address *208.130.29.33* (since reassigned) was used by www.freesoft.org.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] An analysis of this address identified three CIDR prefixes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] *208.128.0.0/11*, a large CIDR block containing over 2 million addresses, had been assigned by ARIN (the North American RIR) to MCI.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Automation Research Systems (ARS), a Virginia VAR, leased an Internet connection from MCI and was assigned the *208.130.28.0/22* block, capable of addressing just over 1000 devices.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] ARS used a */24* block for its publicly accessible servers, of which *208.130.29.33* was one.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] All of these CIDR prefixes would be used at different locations in the network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Outside MCI's network, the *208.128.0.0/11* prefix would be used to direct to MCI traffic bound not only for *208.130.29.33*, but also for any of the roughly two million IP addresses with the same initial 11 bits.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Within MCI's network, *208.130.28.0/22* would become visible, directing traffic to the leased line serving ARS.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Only within the ARS corporate network would the *208.130.29.0/24* prefix have been used.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In routed subnets larger than */31* or */32*, the number of available host addresses is usually reduced by two, namely the largest address, which is reserved as the broadcast address, and the smallest address, which identifies the network itself and is reserved solely for this purpose.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] In such usage, a */31* network, with one binary digit in the host identifier, is unusable, as such a subnet would provide no available host addresses after this reduction.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] RFC 3021 creates an exception to the "host all ones" and "host all zeros" rules to make */31* networks usable for point-to-point links.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] */32* addresses (single-host network) must be accessed by explicit routing rules, as there is no address available for a gateway.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The large address size of IPv6 permitted worldwide route summarization and guaranteed sufficient address pools at each site.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The standard subnet size for IPv6 networks is a */64* block, which is required for the operation of stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] This IPv6 subnetting reference lists the sizes for IPv6 subnetworks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Different types of network links may require different subnet sizes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] The subnet mask separates the bits of the network identifier prefix from the bits of the interface identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Selecting a smaller prefix size results in fewer number of networks covered, but with more addresses within each network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Topologically, the set of subnets described by CIDR represents a cover of the corresponding address space.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] For a fixed n , the set of all $X/n$ subnets constitutes a partition, that is, a cover of non-overlapping sets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Increasing n yields finer and finer subpartitions.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] Thus, two subnets $X/n$ and $Y/m$ are either disjoint or one is a subnet of the other.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR provides fine-grained routing prefix aggregation.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, if the first 20 bits of their network prefixes match, sixteen contiguous */24* networks can be aggregated and advertised to a larger network as a single */20* routing table entry.
[src:cidr-subnetting/classless-inter-domain-routing] This reduces the number of routes that have to be advertised.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] An **Internet Protocol address** (**IP address**) is a numerical label, such as *192.168.1.1* or *2001:0db8:0000:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334*, that is assigned to a device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP addresses serve two main functions: network interface identification, and location addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) was the first standalone specification for the IP address, and has been in use since 1983.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are defined as a 32-bit number, which later then became too small to provide enough addresses as the internet grew, leading to IPv4 address exhaustion over the 2010s.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Its designated successor, IPv6, uses 128 bits for the IP address, giving it a larger address space.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Although IPv6 deployment has been ongoing since the mid-2000s, both IPv4 and IPv6 are still used side-by-side as of 2025.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP addresses are usually displayed in a human-readable notation, but systems may use them in various different computer number formats.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] CIDR notation can also be used to designate how much of the address should be treated as a routing prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] For example, *192.0.2.1/24* indicates that 24 significant bits of the address are the prefix, with the remaining 8 bits used for host addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This is equivalent to the historically used subnet mask (in this case, *255.255.255.0*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The IP address space is managed globally by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) and the five regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IANA assigns blocks of IP addresses to the RIRs, which are responsible for distributing them to local Internet registries in their region, such as internet service providers (ISPs) and large institutions.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Some addresses are reserved for private networks and are not globally unique.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Within a network, the network administrator assigns an IP address to each device.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Such assignments may be on a *static* (fixed or permanent) or *dynamic* basis, depending on network practices and software features.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the European Union, consider IP addresses to be personal data.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] An IP address serves two principal functions: it identifies the host, or more specifically, its network interface, and it provides the location of the host in the network, and thus, the capability of establishing a path to that host.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Its role has been characterized as follows: "A name indicates what we seek.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A route indicates how to get there." The header of each IP packet contains the IP address of the sending host and that of the destination host.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Two versions of the Internet Protocol are in common use on the Internet today.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The original version of the Internet Protocol that was first deployed in 1983 in the ARPANET, the predecessor of the Internet, is Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] By the early 1990s, the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 address space available for assignment to Internet service providers and end-user organizations prompted the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) to explore new technologies to expand addressing capability on the Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The result was a redesign of the Internet Protocol, which eventually became known as Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6) in 1995.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv6 technology was in various testing stages until the mid-2000s, when commercial production deployment commenced.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Today, these two versions of the Internet Protocol are in simultaneous use.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Among other technical changes, each version defines the format of addresses differently.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Because of the historical prevalence of IPv4, the generic term *IP address* typically still refers to the addresses defined by IPv4.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The gap in version sequence between IPv4 and IPv6 resulted from the assignment of version 5 to the experimental Internet Stream Protocol in 1979, which, however, was never referred to as *IPv5*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Versions 1 to 9 were defined, but only 4 and 6 ever gained widespread use.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Transmission Control Protocol (the protocol suite later referred to as *TCP/IP*) versions 1 and 2 were published in 1974 and 1977.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Version 3 was defined in 1978, and version 3.1 is the first version in which TCP is separated from IP.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Version 6 is a synthesis of several suggested versions, version 6 *Simple Internet Protocol*, version 7 *TP/IX: The Next Internet*, version 8 *P.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Internet Protocol*, and version 9 *TCP and UDP with Bigger Addresses (TUBA)*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP networks may be divided into subnetworks in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] For this purpose, an IP address is recognized as consisting of two parts: the *network prefix* in the high-order bits and the remaining bits called the *rest field*, *host identifier*, or *interface identifier* (IPv6), used for host numbering within a network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The subnet mask or CIDR notation determines how the IP address is divided into network and host parts.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The term *subnet mask* is only used within IPv4.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Both IP versions, however, use the CIDR concept and notation.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In this, the IP address is followed by a slash and the number (in decimal) of bits used for the network part, also called the *routing prefix*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The CIDR notation for the same IP address and subnet is *192.0.2.1/24*, because the first 24 bits of the IP address indicate the network and subnet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] An IPv4 address has a size of 32 bits, which limits the address space to 4294967296 (232) addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Of this number, some addresses are reserved for special purposes such as private networks (≈18 million addresses) and multicast addressing (≈270 million addresses).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv4 addresses are usually represented in dot-decimal notation, consisting of four decimal numbers, each ranging from 0 to 255, separated by dots, e.g., *192.0.2.1*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Each part represents a group of 8 bits (an octet) of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In some cases of technical writing, IPv4 addresses may be presented in various hexadecimal, octal, or binary representations.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In the early stages of development of the Internet Protocol, the network number was always the highest-order octet (most significant eight bits).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Because this method allowed for only 256 networks, it soon proved inadequate as additional networks developed that were independent of the existing networks already designated by a network number.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In 1981, the addressing specification was revised with the introduction of classful network architecture.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Classful network design allowed for a larger number of individual network assignments and fine-grained subnetwork design.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The first three bits of the most significant octet of an IP address were defined as the *class* of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Three classes (*A*, *B*, and *C*) were defined for universal unicast addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Depending on the class derived, the network identification was based on octet boundary segments of the entire address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Each class used successively additional octets in the network identifier, thus reducing the possible number of hosts in the higher-order classes (*B* and *C*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The following table gives an overview of this now-obsolete system.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Classful network design served its purpose in the startup stage of the Internet, but it lacked scalability in the face of the rapid expansion of networking in the 1990s.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The class system of the address space was replaced with Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) in 1993.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] CIDR is based on variable-length subnet masking (VLSM) to allow allocation and routing based on arbitrary-length prefixes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Today, remnants of classful network concepts function only in a limited scope as the default configuration parameters of some network software and hardware components (e.g. netmask), and in the technical jargon used in network administrators' discussions.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Early network design, when global end-to-end connectivity was envisioned for communications with all Internet hosts, intended that IP addresses be globally unique.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] However, it was found that this was not always necessary as private networks developed and public address space needed to be conserved.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Computers not connected to the Internet, such as factory machines that communicate only with each other via TCP/IP, need not have globally unique IP addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Today, such private networks are widely used and typically connect to the Internet with network address translation (NAT), when needed.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Three non-overlapping ranges of IPv4 addresses for private networks are reserved.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] These addresses are not routed on the Internet, and thus their use need not be coordinated with an IP address registry.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Any user may use any of the reserved blocks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Typically, a network administrator will divide a block into subnets; for example, many home routers automatically use a default address range of *192.168.0.0* through *192.168.0.255* (*192.168.0.0/24*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In IPv6, the address size was increased from 32 bits in IPv4 to 128 bits, thus providing up to 2128 (approximately 3.403×1038) addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This is deemed sufficient for the foreseeable future.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The intent of the new design was not to provide just a sufficient quantity of addresses, but also to redesign routing in the Internet by allowing more efficient aggregation of subnetwork routing prefixes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This resulted in slower growth of routing tables in routers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The smallest possible individual allocation is a subnet for 264 hosts, which is the square of the size of the entire IPv4 Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] At these levels, actual address utilization ratios will be small on any IPv6 network segment.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The new design also provides the opportunity to separate the addressing infrastructure of a network segment, i.e., the local administration of the segment's available space, from the addressing prefix used to route traffic to and from external networks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv6 has facilities that automatically change the routing prefix of entire networks, should the global connectivity or the routing policy change, without requiring internal redesign or manual renumbering.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The large number of IPv6 addresses allows large blocks to be assigned for specific purposes and, where appropriate, to be aggregated for efficient routing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] With a large address space, there is no need to have complex address conservation methods as used in CIDR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] All modern desktop and enterprise server operating systems include native support for IPv6, but it is not yet widely deployed in other devices, such as residential networking routers, voice over IP (VoIP) and multimedia equipment, and some networking hardware.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Just as IPv4 reserves addresses for private networks, blocks of addresses are set aside in IPv6.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In IPv6, these are referred to as unique local addresses (ULAs).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The routing prefix *fc00::/7* is reserved for this block, which is divided into two */8* blocks with different implied policies.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The addresses include a 40-bit pseudorandom number that minimizes the risk of address collisions if sites merge or packets are misrouted.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Early practices used a different block for this purpose (*fec0::*), dubbed site-local addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] However, the definition of what constituted a *site* remained unclear and the poorly defined addressing policy created ambiguities for routing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This address type was abandoned and must not be used in new systems.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Addresses starting with *fe80::*, called link-local addresses, are assigned to interfaces for communication on the attached link.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The addresses are automatically generated by the operating system for each network interface.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This provides instant and automatic communication between all IPv6 hosts on a link.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This feature is used in the lower layers of IPv6 network administration, such as for the Neighbor Discovery Protocol.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Private and link-local address prefixes may not be routed on the public Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP addresses are assigned to a host either dynamically as they join the network, or persistently by configuration of the host hardware or software.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Persistent configuration is also known as using a **static IP address**.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In contrast, when a computer's IP address is assigned each time it restarts, this is known as using a **dynamic IP address**.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Dynamic IP addresses are assigned by the network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is the most frequently used technology for assigning addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] It avoids the administrative burden of assigning specific static addresses to each device on a network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] It also allows devices to share the limited address space on a network if only some of them are online at a particular time.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Typically, dynamic IP configuration is enabled by default in modern desktop operating systems.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The address assigned with DHCP is associated with a *lease* and usually has an expiration period.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] If the lease is not renewed by the host before expiry, the address may be assigned to another device.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Some DHCP implementations attempt to reassign the same IP address to a host, based on its MAC address, each time it joins the network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A network administrator may configure a DHCP server to allocate specific IP addresses to specific MAC addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] DHCP is not the only technology used to assign IP addresses dynamically.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Bootstrap Protocol is a similar protocol and predecessor to DHCP.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Dialup and some broadband networks use dynamic address features of the Point-to-Point Protocol.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Computers and equipment used for the network infrastructure, such as routers and mail servers, are typically configured with static addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In the absence or failure of static or dynamic address configurations, an operating system may assign a link-local address to a host using stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Address block *169.254.0.0/16* is defined for the special use of link-local addressing for IPv4 networks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In IPv6, every interface, whether using static or dynamic addresses, also receives a link-local address automatically in the block *fe80::/10*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] These addresses are only valid on the link, such as a local network segment or point-to-point connection, to which a host is connected.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] These addresses are not routable and, like private addresses, cannot be the source or destination of packets traversing the Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] When the link-local IPv4 address block was reserved, no standards existed for mechanisms of address autoconfiguration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Filling the void, Microsoft developed a protocol called Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA), whose first public implementation appeared in Windows 98.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] APIPA has been deployed on millions of machines and became a *de facto* standard in the industry.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In May 2005, the IETF defined a formal standard for it.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] An IP address conflict occurs when two devices on the same local physical or wireless network claim to have the same IP address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A second assignment of an address generally stops the IP functionality of one or both of the devices.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Many modern operating systems notify the administrator of IP address conflicts.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] When IP addresses are assigned by multiple people and systems with differing methods, any of them may be at fault.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] If one of the devices involved in the conflict is the default gateway access beyond the LAN for all devices on the LAN, all devices may be impaired.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP addresses are classified into several classes of operational characteristics: unicast, multicast, anycast and broadcast addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The most common concept of an IP address is in unicast addressing, available in both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] It normally refers to a single sender or a single receiver, and can be used for both sending and receiving.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Usually, a unicast address is associated with a single device or host, but a device or host may have more than one unicast address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Sending the same data to multiple unicast addresses requires the sender to send all the data many times over, once for each recipient.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Broadcasting is an addressing technique available in IPv4 to address data to all possible destinations on a network in one transmission operation as an *all-hosts broadcast*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] All receivers capture the network packet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In addition, a more limited directed broadcast uses the all-ones host address with the network prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] For example, the destination address used for directed broadcast to devices on the network *192.0.2.0/24* is *192.0.2.255*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv6 does not implement broadcast addressing and replaces it with multicast to the specially defined all-nodes multicast address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A multicast address is associated with a group of interested receivers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In IPv4, addresses *224.0.0.0* through *239.255.255.255* (the former Class D addresses) are designated as multicast addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IPv6 uses the address block with the prefix *ff00::/8* for multicast.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In either case, the sender sends a single datagram from its unicast address to the multicast group address, and the intermediary routers take care of making copies and sending them to all interested receivers (those that have joined the corresponding multicast group).
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Like broadcast and multicast, anycast is a one-to-many routing topology.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] However, the data stream is not transmitted to all receivers, just the one that the router decides is closest in the network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Anycast addressing is a built-in feature of IPv6.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In IPv4, anycast addressing is implemented with Border Gateway Protocol using the shortest-path metric to choose destinations.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Anycast methods are useful for global load balancing and are commonly used in distributed DNS systems.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A host may use geolocation to deduce the geographic position of its communicating peer.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] This is typically done by retrieving geolocation info about the IP address of the other node from a database.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A public IP address is a globally routable unicast IP address, meaning that the address is not an address reserved for use in private networks, such as those reserved by RFC 1918, or the various IPv6 address formats of local scope or site-local scope, for example, for link-local addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Public IP addresses may be used for communication between hosts on the global Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In a home situation, a public IP address is the IP address assigned to the home's network by the ISP.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In this case, it is also locally visible by logging into the router configuration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Most public IP addresses change relatively often.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Any type of IP address that changes is called a dynamic IP address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In home networks, the ISP usually assigns a dynamic IP.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] If an ISP gave a home network an unchanging address, it is more likely to be abused by customers who host websites from home, or by hackers who can try the same IP address over and over until they breach a network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] A common practice is to have a NAT device mask many devices in a private network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Only the public interfaces of the NAT device need to have an Internet-routable address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The NAT device maps different IP addresses on the private network to different TCP or UDP port numbers on the public network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In residential networks, NAT functions are usually implemented in a residential gateway.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In this scenario, the computers connected to the router have private IP addresses, and the router has a public address on its external interface to communicate on the Internet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] The internal computers appear to share one public IP address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In March 2024, the Supreme Court of Canada decided that the IP addresses are protected private information under the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*, with police searches requiring a warrant in order to obtain them.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] IP addresses are considered personal data by the European Commission and are protected by the *General Data Protection Regulation*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] In the United States, the California Consumer Privacy Act only protects IP addresses that link to any particular consumer or household; otherwise it is not private data and is not protected under American law.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Computer operating systems provide various diagnostic tools to examine network interfaces and address configuration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/ip-address] Microsoft Windows provides the command-line interface tools ipconfig and netsh and users of Unix-like systems may use ifconfig, netstat, route, lanstat, fstat, and iproute2 utilities to accomplish the task.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] A **subnet**, or **subnetwork**, is a logical subdivision of an IP network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The practice of dividing a network into two or more networks is called **subnetting**.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Computers that belong to the same subnet are addressed with an identical group of most-significant bits of their IP addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This results in the logical division of an IP address into two fields: the *network number* or *routing prefix*, and the *rest field* or *host identifier*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The *rest field* is an identifier for a specific host or network interface.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The *routing prefix* may be expressed as the first address of a network, written in Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) notation, followed by a slash character (*/*), and ending with the bit-length of the prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For example, *198.51.100.0/24* is the prefix of the Internet Protocol version 4 network starting at the given address, having 24 bits allocated for the network prefix, and the remaining 8 bits reserved for host addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The IPv6 address specification *2001:db8::/32* is a large address block with 296 addresses, having a 32-bit routing prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For IPv4, a network may also be characterized by its **subnet mask** or **netmask**, which is the bitmask that, when applied by a bitwise AND operation to any IP address in the network, yields the routing prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Subnet masks are also expressed in dot-decimal notation like an IP address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Traffic is exchanged between subnets through routers when the routing prefixes of the source address and the destination address differ.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] A router serves as a logical or physical boundary between the subnets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The benefits of subnetting an existing network vary with each deployment scenario.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In the address allocation architecture of the Internet, using CIDR, and in large organizations, efficient allocation of address space is necessary.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Subnetting may also enhance routing efficiency or have advantages in network management when subnets are administratively controlled by different entities in a larger organization.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Subnets may be arranged logically in a hierarchical architecture, partitioning an organization's network address space into a tree-like routing structure or other structures, such as meshes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Computers participating in an IP network have at least one network address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Usually, this address is unique to each device and can either be configured automatically by a network service with the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), manually by an administrator, or automatically by the operating system with stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] An address fulfills the functions of identifying the host and locating it on the network in destination routing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The most common network addressing architecture is Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), but its successor, IPv6, has been increasingly deployed since approximately 2006.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In both architectures, an IP address is divided into two logical parts, the *network prefix* and the *host identifier*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] All hosts on a subnet have the same network prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This prefix occupies the most significant bits of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The number of bits allocated within a network to the prefix may vary between subnets, depending on the network architecture.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The host identifier is a unique local identification and is either a host number on the local network or an interface identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Routers constitute logical or physical borders between the subnets and manage traffic between them.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Each subnet is served by a designated default router but may consist internally of multiple physical Ethernet segments interconnected by network switches.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The routing prefix of an address is identified by the *subnet mask*, written in the same form used for IP addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For example, the subnet mask for a routing prefix that is composed of the most-significant 24 bits of an IPv4 address is written as *255.255.255.0*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The modern standard form of specification of the network prefix is CIDR notation, used for both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] It counts the number of bits in the prefix and appends that number to the address after a *slash* (/) character separator.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This notation was introduced with Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In IPv6 this is the only standards-based form to denote network or routing prefixes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In classful networking in IPv4, before the introduction of CIDR, the network prefix could be directly obtained from the IP address, based on its highest-order bit sequence.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This determined the class (A, B, C) of the address and, therefore, the subnet mask.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Since the introduction of CIDR, however, the assignment of an IP address to a network interface requires two parameters, the address and a subnet mask.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Given an IPv4 source address, its associated subnet mask, and the destination address, a router can determine whether the destination is on a locally connected network or a remote network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The subnet mask of the destination is not needed, and is generally not known to a router.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For IPv6, however, on-link determination is different in detail and requires the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP).
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] IPv6 address assignment to an interface carries no requirement of a matching on-link prefix and vice versa, with the exception of link-local addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Since each locally connected subnet must be represented by a separate entry in the routing tables of each connected router, subnetting increases routing complexity.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] However, by careful design of the network, routes to collections of more distant subnets within the branches of a tree hierarchy can be aggregated into a supernetwork and represented by single routes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] An IPv4 subnet mask consists of 32 bits; it is a sequence of ones (*1*) followed by a block of zeros (*0*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The ones indicate bits in the address used for the network prefix, and the trailing block of zeros designates that part as being the host identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The following example shows the separation of the network prefix and the host identifier from an address (*192.0.2.130*) and its associated */24* subnet mask (*255.255.255.0*).
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The operation is visualized in a table using binary address formats.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The result of the bitwise AND operation of IP address and the subnet mask is the network prefix *192.0.2.0*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The host part, which is *130*, is derived by the bitwise AND operation of the address and the ones' complement of the subnet mask.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Subnetting is the process of designating some high-order bits from the host part as part of the network prefix and adjusting the subnet mask appropriately.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This divides a network into smaller subnets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The following diagram modifies the above example by moving 2 bits from the host part to the network prefix to form four smaller subnets, each one quarter of the previous size.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] IPv4 uses specially designated address formats to facilitate recognition of special address functionality.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The first and the last subnets obtained by subnetting a larger network have traditionally had a special designation and, early on, special usage implications.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In addition, IPv4 uses the *all ones* host address, i.e., the last address within a network, for broadcast transmission to all hosts on the link.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The first subnet obtained from subnetting a larger network has all bits in the subnet bit group set to zero.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The last subnet obtained from subnetting a larger network has all bits in the subnet bit group set to one.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] It is therefore called the *all-ones subnet*.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The IETF originally discouraged the production use of these two subnets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] When the prefix length is not available, the larger network and the first subnet have the same address, which may lead to confusion.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Similar confusion is possible with the broadcast address at the end of the last subnet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Therefore, reserving the subnet values consisting of all zeros and all ones on the public Internet was recommended, reducing the number of available subnets by two for each subnetting.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This inefficiency was removed, and the practice was declared obsolete in 1995, and is only relevant when dealing with legacy equipment.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Although the all-zeros and the all-ones host values are reserved for the network address of the subnet and its broadcast address, respectively, in systems using CIDR, all subnets are available in a subdivided network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For example, a */24* network can be divided into sixteen usable */28* networks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The number of subnets available and the number of possible hosts in a network may be readily calculated.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] For instance, the *192.168.5.0/24* network may be subdivided into the following four */26* subnets.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The highlighted two address bits become part of the network number in this process.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The remaining bits after the subnet bits are used for addressing hosts within the subnet.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In the above example, the subnet mask consists of 26 bits, making it 255.255.255.192, leaving 6 bits for the host identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] This allows for 62 host combinations (26−2).
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In general, the number of available hosts on a subnet is 2*h*−2, where *h* is the number of bits used for the host portion of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The number of available subnets is 2*n*, where *n* is the number of bits used for the network portion of the address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] There is an exception to this rule for 31-bit subnet masks,, which means the host identifier is only one bit long for two permissible addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In such networks, usually point-to-point links, only two hosts (the endpoints) may be connected, and a specification of network and broadcast addresses is not necessary.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The design of the IPv6 address space differs significantly from IPv4.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The primary reason for subnetting in IPv4 is to improve efficiency in the utilization of the relatively small address space available, particularly to enterprises.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] No such limitations exist in IPv6, as the large address space available, even to end-users, is not a limiting factor.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] As in IPv4, subnetting in IPv6 is based on the concepts of variable-length subnet masking (VLSM) and the Classless Inter-Domain Routing methodology.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] It is used to route traffic between the global allocation spaces and within customer networks between subnets and the Internet at large.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] A compliant IPv6 subnet always uses addresses with 64 bits in the host identifier.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Given the address size of 128 bits, it therefore has a /64 routing prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Although it is technically possible to use smaller subnets, they are impractical for local area networks based on Ethernet technology, because 64 bits are required for stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The Internet Engineering Task Force recommends the use of */127* subnets for point-to-point links, which have only two hosts.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] IPv6 does not implement special address formats for broadcast traffic or network numbers, and thus all addresses in a subnet are acceptable for host addressing.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The all-zeroes address is reserved as the subnet-router anycast address.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The subnet router anycast address is the lowest address in the subnet, so it looks like the “network address”.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] If a router has multiple subnets on the same link, then it has multiple subnet router anycast addresses on that link.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] The first and last address in any network or subnet is not allowed to be assigned to any individual host.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] In the past, the recommended allocation for an IPv6 customer site was an address space with a 48-bit (*/48*) prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] However, this recommendation was revised to encourage smaller blocks, for example, using 56-bit prefixes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/subnetwork] Another common allocation size for residential customer networks has a 64-bit prefix.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] A **supernetwork**, or **supernet**, is an Internet Protocol (IP) network that is formed by aggregation of multiple networks (or subnets) into a larger network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The new routing prefix for the aggregate network represents the constituent networks in a single routing table entry.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The process of forming a supernet is called **supernetting**, **prefix aggregation**, **route aggregation**, or **route summarization**.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting within the Internet serves as a strategy to avoid fragmentation of the IP address space by using a hierarchical allocation system that delegates control of segments of address space to regional Internet registries.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] This method facilitates regional route aggregation.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The benefits of supernetting are efficiencies gained in routers in terms of memory storage of route information and processing overhead when matching routes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting, however, can introduce interoperability issues and other risks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] In IP networking terminology, a supernet is a block of contiguous subnetworks addressed as a single subnet from the perspective of the larger network.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernets are always larger than their component networks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting is the process of aggregating routes to multiple smaller networks, thus saving storage space in the routing table, simplifying routing decisions and reducing route advertisements to neighboring gateways.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting has helped address the increasing size of routing tables as the Internet has expanded.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting in large, complex networks can isolate topology changes from other routers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] This can improve the stability of the network by limiting the propagation of routing changes in the event of a network link failure.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] If a router only advertises a summary route to the next router, then it does not need to advertise any changes to specific subnets within the summarized range.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] This can significantly reduce any unnecessary routing updates following a topology change.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Hence, it increases the speed of convergence resulting in a more stable environment.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Supernetting requires the use of routing protocols that support Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Interior Gateway Routing Protocol, Exterior Gateway Protocol and version 1 of the Routing Information Protocol (RIPv1) assume classful addressing, and therefore cannot transmit the subnet mask information required for supernetting.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) supports CIDR.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] By default, EIGRP summarizes the routes within the routing table and forwards these summarized routes to its peers.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Other routing protocols with CIDR support include RIPv2, Open Shortest Path First, IS-IS and Border Gateway Protocol.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] A company that operates 150 accounting services in each of 50 districts has a router in each office connected with a Frame Relay link to its corporate headquarters.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Without supernetting, the routing table on any given router might have to account for 150 routers in each of the 50 districts, or 7500 different networks.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] However, if a hierarchical addressing system is implemented with supernetting, then each district has a centralized site as an interconnection point.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Each route is summarized before being advertised to other districts.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Each router now only recognizes its own subnet and the other 49 summarized routes.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The determination of the summary route on a router involves the recognition of the number of highest-order bits that match all addresses.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The summary route is calculated as follows.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Secondly, the bits at which the common pattern of digits ends are located.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Lastly, the number of common bits is counted.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The summary route is found by setting the remaining bits to zero, as shown below.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] It is followed by a slash and then the number of common bits.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] It must be assured that the missing networks do not exist outside of this route.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] In another example, an ISP is assigned a block of IP addresses by a regional Internet registry (RIR) of 172.1.0.0 to 172.1.255.255.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] The ISP might then assign subnetworks to each of their downstream clients, e.g., *Customer A* will have the range 172.1.1.0 to 172.1.1.255, *Customer B* would receive the range 172.1.2.0 to 172.1.2.255 and *Customer C* would receive the range 172.1.3.0 to 172.1.3.255, and so on.
[src:cidr-subnetting/supernetwork] Instead of an entry for each of the subnets 172.1.1.x and 172.1.2.x, etc., the ISP could aggregate the entire 172.1.x.x address range and advertise the network 172.1.0.0/16, which would reduce the number of entries in the global routing table.
